04372nmm a2200589Ia 9780520395077DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20242024cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203950777 a10.1525/97805203950772doi  a(DE-B1597)658566  a(OCoLC)1382281967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS247.D74bA46 2024 7aSOC0080702bisacsh04a307.76095357223/eng/202305201 aAlMutawa, Rana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEveryday Life in the Spectacular City :bMaking Home in Dubai /cRana AlMutawa. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. (In)Authenticity in Brand Dubai -- t2. Negotiating Belonging in Dubai’s Glitzy, Neoliberal Spaces -- t3. Globalization and Diversity at a Cosmopolitan Crossroads -- t4. An Appropriately Modern City -- t5. The Costs and Benefits of Safety in Sanitized Spaces -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEveryday Life in the Spectacular City is a groundbreaking urban ethnography that reveals how middle-class citizens and longtime residents of Dubai interact with the city's so-called superficial spaces to create meaningful social lives. Rana AlMutawa shows that inhabitants adapt themselves to top-down development projects, from big malls to megaprojects. These structures serve residents' evolving social needs, transforming Dubai's spectacular spaces into personally important cultural sites. These practices are significant because they expand our understanding of agency as not only subversive but also adaptive. Through extensive fieldwork, AlMutawa, herself an Emirati native to Dubai, finds a more nuanced story of belonging. This story does not seek to uncover the ";real"; city that lies beneath the veneer of the spectacle, but rather to demonstrate that social meanings and forms of belonging take place within the spectacle itself. By offering an alternative to the discourse of authenticity and elucidating the dynamics of ambivalent belonging, AlMutawa belies stereotypes that portray Dubai's developments as alienating and inherently disempowering. Everyday Life in the Spectacular City speaks beyond the Middle East to a globalized phenomenon, for Dubai's spectacles are unexceptional in today's changing world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBelonging (Social psychology)zUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate)2DLC. 0aBelonging (Social psychology)zUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate). 0aCity and town lifezUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate)2DLC. 0aCity and town lifezUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate). 0aMiddle classzUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate)2DLC. 0aMiddle classzUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate). 0aUrban anthropologyzUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate)2DLC. 0aUrban anthropologyzUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Middle Eastern Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520395077?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520395077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520395077/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles